T1  - Scripts as Determinants of Purposeful Behavior in Organizations
AU  - Lord, Robert G.
AU  - Kernan, Mary C.
Y1  - 1987/04/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4307831
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4307831
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 265
EP  - 277
VL  - 12
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper focuses on the role cognitive scripts, a unique type of knowledge schema, play in generating purposive behaviors in organizations. Three separate but complementary areas of research (Scheme Theory, Control Theory, and Goal Setting Theory) clarify the processes that link script-type structures to purposeful behavior. Finally, implications and extensions of this comprehensive framework based on previously identified content, structure, and process issues are considered.
AB  - This paper focuses on the role cognitive scripts, a unique type of knowledge schema, play in generating purposive behaviors in organizations. Three separate but complementary areas of research (Scheme Theory, Control Theory, and Goal Setting Theory) clarify the processes that link script-type structures to purposeful behavior. Finally, implications and extensions of this comprehensive framework based on previously identified content, structure, and process issues are considered.
