TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Interactionist Perspective on Newcomer Socialization Rates
AU  - Reichers, Arnon E.
Y1  - 1987/04/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4307838
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4307838
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 278
EP  - 287
VL  - 12
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A symbolic interactionist perspective on the genesis of meaning and identity is used as a general theoretical framework to explain the specifics of newcomer socialization processes in organizations. This framework suggests that interactions with insiders in the setting may be an important, but largely overlooked, influence on the rate at which newcomers negotiate the first (encounter) stage of the socialization process. The role of interactions between newcomers and insiders is emphasized as the primary vehicle through which initial socialization occurs. A model of the interactionist perspective is presented and directions for future research are discussed.
AB  - A symbolic interactionist perspective on the genesis of meaning and identity is used as a general theoretical framework to explain the specifics of newcomer socialization processes in organizations. This framework suggests that interactions with insiders in the setting may be an important, but largely overlooked, influence on the rate at which newcomers negotiate the first (encounter) stage of the socialization process. The role of interactions between newcomers and insiders is emphasized as the primary vehicle through which initial socialization occurs. A model of the interactionist perspective is presented and directions for future research are discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4307838
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1987.4307838
Y2  - 2026/04/24
